Some notes on simulating polydisperse systems

Winter meeting 2025

24w37b

Summary from reading.

This was supposed to be a TL;DR, but it ended being too long.
The more I read, the less I understand.

  • The basic principle is order1 other order2

    • Phase with no long-range order, occurring in a region below an ordered phase on the temperature scale
    • Apparently this happens in spin-glasses but nobody knows why.
    • Happens a lot in active systems, but it is not ubiquitous to activity.

  • What conditions does a system need to observe reentrancy?

    • Some people talk about the coexistence of order and disorder.
    • Reentrancy seems to appear in systems with NN+NNN interactions.
    • It seems that anisotropic interactions play some sort of role.
      • Although, in Kagome 16-vertex model, pure NNN induce reentrancy.
      • But anisotropic bonds induce special features.
    • Partial disorder in the GS
    • There is no concrete theoretical explanation on why reentrant phases occur.
    • Many people think that there should be at least a partially disordered phase next to an ordered phase or another partially disordered phase in the GS.
      • The partial disorder is due to competition between different interactions.
    • Seems that reentrant region favor the occurrence of reentrancy.
      • But alone cannot cause reentrancy.

  • Weird stuff that apparently is important

    • Coordination number at disordered site large enough to influence the neighboring ordered sites.
      • May have an upper limit to avoid disorder contamination. The right number seems to be 4.
        • What happens in mixed coordination lattices?
        • What happens in decimated lattices?
    • When a phase transition occurs between states of different symmetries that have no special groum-subgroup relation, it is generally accepted that the transition is of first order. However, reentrant phenomenon is a symmetry-breaking alternative that allows one ordered phase to change into another incompatible ordered phase by going through an intermediate reentrant phase.
      • Under which conditions does a system prefer reentrancy over a 1st order transition?

  • Stuff I don't understand

    • What is a disorder line?

In summary, there is no summary.

Wht?

  • So, what are we doing?
    We are starting from a 2in/2out state with field in the axis, and then rotating it towards the axis.

By doing this, we would expect to have at the end the 4in/4out GS, but we sometimes don't.

  • And what are we seeing?
    For very slow rotations, the system does not reach the GS, but for quick rotations, the system reaches the GS.
    Here slow, and quick are not even really far apart. For the most part, we are already reaching the GS, so the 'transition' dynamics occur for

The magnitude of the field only accelerates this process, as seen in this figure. There are no signs of suppression from any of the tested parameters.

From left to right, the red lines on the first row displace to the left and increase sharper. I am not sure if they increase enough for them to have a divergence in its derivative at the 'transition angle'.

So, another thing that we have, and I will plot only in the range since it seems to be the important one. The vertices counts for all fields at the last frame.
Here we are basically answering the question: if I change the field, in which state do I end?

We see that low fields, the does not matter that much. However the interesting part comes when we have high fields. We have a different behavior for slow and for fast .
For very slow velocities, the system never reaches the GS, but the higher the field the more it 'goes back'.
For intermediate velocities, the system seems to have a sweet spot around 3 to 5 mT in which it almost reaches the GS before going back to a mixed state.
For high velocities, the system does nothing for low fields, but suddently plop! it just decays into the GS.

For a moment, at the tail of the graph, it seems that the system decays at bit, just a tiny bit!

  • Is it just numerical error?
  • Is it that the graph will eventually drop again for very high fields?
    • Unfortunately I have no way of testing this, I think that 20mT is the maximum we can do.
    • But this would mean that for quick rotations, and very high fields, the system dows not decay to the GS. Which is plausible but I don't think it is very interesting.

From which we see some important stuff

  • For high frequencies, we see no area, which means that there is no bump
  • There is non-zero area in the regime which is what we kind of expected.
  • More interestingly, but not so much is the fact the this graph has a maximum around Hz, meaning..
    • What happens in the asymptotic limit as . (Note: I call it asymptotic since there is no rotation in )
    • Will this graph go to zero?
      • If so, then there is a flat section in the graph, meaning that there are full vertices with
      • If so, then the system reaches the GS again in principle for infinitely slow

I am running a sim at a rate of which is 10 times slower than the slowest sim presented so far. I will update this graph and see what happens in this case.

Additionally, if this is true...
I think that the mechanism behind the ordered phase at very low and high frequencies is different.
One would look like a stretching of the counts, and the other like making it more compact. But I still need to develop this idea

Why is this happening?
I have no idea, well kind of, this is just me yapping, and have no idea on how to justify any of this

  • So apparently, some people attribute reentrant phases to competition between two or more mechanisms. So, what exactly is competing here?
  • Perhaps, when the system goes moderately slow, it can explore the phase space and can a bunch of states to try and reach the particular GS at the specific angle it is currently in.
  • As it is rotating, the magnitude of the interactions in different directions in changing as well, this should have some sort of effect.
  • We already saw that very low fields are enough to stuck the system, although this happened for the thermal system. But from the quenches in 24w19, the system equilibrates at 5mT, which is (again) low field.
  • When the system goes fast, and idk how to justify this, it just jumps over all of those intermediate states, and before the system notices, magnetic interactions already won over anything else, plus magnification of anisotropic attractive interactions, making it easier to directly go into the fully charged GS.

My question of, what happens when we go extremely slow? is yet to be answered, but I hope something of this yapping holds by then.
